<http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/resource/monument_record_no/260M> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/definition/monument_desc> "Lewin's Mead Meeting House, a Unitarian chapel, located on the north side of Lewins Mead. The building replaced an earlier meeting-house, built in 1693-94, which was demolished in 1787. The present structure built in the late 1780s or very early 1790s to a design by William Blackburn of London and was registered in 1791.\r\nThe meeting house is constructed of rendered stone rubble with ashlar dressings; ashlar facing to the front wall above a rusticated lower stage; main roof hipped and slated, with extension to south gable/pediment. In plan the main building is a broad rectangle with projecting pedimented centrepiece on the south with open semi-circular porch. Large tripartite window with arched head above porch, also one each end of building and three in north wall. Interior of 45ft. by 70ft.; galleries to east, west and south, with semi-circular staircases. Pulpit on north wall. Ceiling divided into panels. Later additions of ancillary buildings.\r\nThe front walls, gates and railings are also listed Grade II*. The Sunday school and Tower House are listed, together, as Grade II."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/dataset/Bristol_Monuments.csv>.
